  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do insurance deductibles work?",
  "response": "Insurance deductibles are the amounts you are required to pay out of pocket before your insurance company begins to cover the costs of a claim. Here\u2019s how they generally work:\n\n1. **Types of deductibles**: Deductibles can vary by type of insurance, including health, auto, homeowners, and others. Each policy may have different deductible amounts based on the terms you agree to when you purchase your insurance.\n\n2. **How it applies**:\n   - **Example scenario**: If you have a health insurance policy with a deductible of $1,000 and you incur medical expenses of $3,000, you would need to pay the first $1,000 yourself. After meeting your deductible, your insurer would start to pay their share of the expenses. If your plan covers 80%, they would then pay 80% of the remaining $2,000 (the amount over the deductible), and you would be responsible for the remaining 20%.\n   - **In auto insurance**: If you have an auto insurance policy with a $500 deductible and you get into an accident that causes $2,000 in damage, you would pay the first $500. Your insurer would then cover the remaining $1,500.\n\n3. **Annual vs. per-incident**: Some deductibles are annual, meaning you only have to meet the deductible once per policy year. Others may be per incident or per service. In health insurance, for example, there may be separate deductibles for individual care versus family care.\n\n4. **Higher deductibles, lower premiums**: Generally, policies with higher deductibles have lower monthly premiums because you are taking on a larger share of the initial costs. This can be a good option if you are generally healthy, have fewer claims, or can afford to pay a larger out-of-pocket amount when something does happen.\n\n5. **Exceptions and out-of-pocket maximums**: Some services may not be subject to the deductible (for instance, certain preventive services in health insurance). Additionally, most plans have an out-of-pocket maximum, which caps the total amount you will pay in a given year. Once you reach that limit, the insurance company pays 100% of covered expenses for the remainder of the year.\n\nUnderstanding your deductible is crucial in managing your insurance costs and making informed decisions about your coverage. Always read the terms of your insurance policy or consult with your insurance agent for specific details tailored to your plan.",
